proof.p:
Using the definition of the derivative, we write \sin'(x) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\sin(x+h)-\sin(x)}{h}. The sum identity for sine allows us to rewrite \sin(x+h) = \sin(x)\cos(h)+\cos(x)\sin(h), so that the derivative can be rewritten 
                    \sin'(x) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\sin(x)\cos(h) + \cos(x) \sin(h) - \sin(x)}{h}
                     &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\sin(x) \cdot (\cos(h) - 1) + \cos(x) \cdot \sin(h)}{h} 
                     &= \lim_{h \to 0} \sin(x) \cdot \frac{\cos(h)-1}{h} + \cos(x) \frac{\sin(h)}{h}.
                 Because \sin(x) and \cos(x) do not depend on h, they play the role of a constant multiple. By the rules for a limit of a sum and the limit of a constant multiple, we can write \sin'(x) = \sin(x) \cos'(0) + \cos(x) \sin'(0) = 0 \cdot \sin(x) + 1 \cdot \cos(x) = \cos(x).

Using the definition of the derivative, we write \cos'(x) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\cos(x+h)-\cos(x)}{h}. The sum identity for cosine allows us to rewrite \cos(x+h) = \cos(x)\cos(h)-\sin(x)\sin(h), so that the derivative can be rewritten 
                    \cos'(x) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\cos(x)\cos(h) - \sin(x) \sin(h) - \cos(x)}{h}
                     &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\cos(x) \cdot (\cos(h) - 1) - \sin(x) \cdot \sin(h)}{h} 
                     &= \lim_{h \to 0} \cos(x) \cdot \frac{\cos(h)-1}{h} - \sin(x) \frac{\sin(h)}{h}.
                 We can therefore write \cos'(x) = \cos(x) \cos'(0) - \sin(x) \sin'(0) = 0 \cdot \cos(x) - 1 \cdot \sin(x) = -\sin(x).

The proofs for these rules are all based on the definitions of these trigonometric functions in terms of sine and cosine. 
                     \tan(x) = \frac{\sin(x)}{\cos(x)} \qquad & \qquad \sec(x) = \frac{1}{\cos(x)} 
                     \cot(x) = \frac{\cos(x)}{\sin(x)} \qquad & \qquad \csc(x) = \frac{1}{\sin(x)} 
                 We will look at the derivatives of \tan(x) and \sec(x) and leave the other two proofs to the reader.

Because \tan(x) is defined as a quotient, we compute its derivative using the quotient rule. 
                     \frac{d}{dx}[\tan(x)] &= \frac{d}{dx}[\frac{\sin(x)}{\cos(x)}] 
                     &= \frac{\cos(x) \sin'(x) - \sin(x) \cos'(x)}{\cos^2(x)} 
                     &= \frac{\cos(x) \cdot \cos(x) - \sin(x) \cdot (-\sin(x))}{\cos^2(x)}
                     &=\frac{\cos^2(x) + \sin^2(x)}{\cos^2(x)} 
                     &= \frac{1}{\cos^2(x)} = \sec^2(x)

assemblage.p:
Let u represent any expression that depends on x.
                 \frac{d}{dx}[\sin(u)] &= \cos(u) \frac{du}{dx} 
                 \frac{d}{dx}[\cos(u)] &= -\sin(u) \frac{du}{dx} 
                 \frac{d}{dx}[\tan(u)] &= \sec^2(u) \frac{du}{dx} 
                 \frac{d}{dx}[\cot(u)] &= -\csc^2(u) \frac{du}{dx} 
                 \frac{d}{dx}[\sec(u)] &= \sec(u) \tan(u) \frac{du}{dx} 
                 \frac{d}{dx}[\csc(u)] &= -\csc(u) \cot(u) \frac{du}{dx}
